0.1 R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

summary(cars)
##      speed           dist       
##  Min.   : 4.0   Min.   :  2.00  
##  1st Qu.:12.0   1st Qu.: 26.00  
##  Median :15.0   Median : 36.00  
##  Mean   :15.4   Mean   : 42.98  
##  3rd Qu.:19.0   3rd Qu.: 56.00  
##  Max.   :25.0   Max.   :120.00

0.2 Including Plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

3.1 Distance methods

Calculation of distance matrix with dist(). This function computes and returns the distance matrix computed by using the specified distance measure to compute the distances between the rows of a data matrix.

The distance can be measured with:

  • “euclidean”,
  • “maximum”,
  • “manhattan”,
  • …
varechem.st <- scale(varechem)
# method = 'euclidean'
varechem.dist <- dist(varechem.st, method = 'euclidean')
round(varechem.dist,2)

Create an image of dist matrix

varechem.dist.m <- as.matrix(varechem.dist)
dim(varechem.dist.m)
## [1] 24 24
image(1:24,1:24,varechem.dist.m,
      xlab = 'site number',
      ylab = 'site number',
      main='Distance matrix')

3.2 Hierarchical cluster analysis

Hierarchical cluster analysis on a set of dissimilarities and methods for analyzing it.

Methods: - “ward.D”, - “ward.D2”, - “single”, - “complete”, - “average” (= UPGMA) - …

vare.clust <- hclust(varechem.dist, method = 'complete')
vare.clust
## 
## Call:
## hclust(d = varechem.dist, method = "complete")
## 
## Cluster method   : complete 
## Distance         : euclidean 
## Number of objects: 24
plot(vare.clust)

plot(vare.clust, ylab='Distance', sub='', hang = -1)
rect.hclust(vare.clust, k=4, border = 'red')

#install.packages("factoextra")
library(factoextra)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa
fviz_dend(vare.clust, k=4, y='Distance')
## Registered S3 method overwritten by 'dendextend':
##   method     from 
##   rev.hclust vegan

fviz_dend(vare.clust, k=4, y='Distance', type = 'circ')

fviz_dend(vare.clust, k=4, y='Distance', type = 'phyl')

3.2.1 Challange

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
# cluster
plot(vare.clust, ylab='Distance', sub='', hang = -1)
rect.hclust(vare.clust, k=4, border = 'red')

# PCA biplot
biplot(rda(varechem,scale = T), main='PCA')

## 
##  Serenoa repens IR quality study 
##

##  The y-axis unit is absorbance.
##

##  399.2123 to 3999.837 wavenumber
##  There are 1868 frequency values.
##  The frequency resolution is
##  1.9286 wavenumber/point.
## 
## 
##  The spectra are divided into 4 groups: 
## 
##   group no.   color symbol alt.sym
## 1 adSrE  10 #984EA3     15       d
## 2   EPO   1 #377EB8      2       b
## 3    OO   1 #4DAF4A      3       c
## 4  pSrE   4 #E41A1C      1       a
## 
## 
## *** Note: this is an S3 object
## of class 'Spectra'

A collection of 14 IR and NMR spectra of essential oil extracted from the palm Serenoa repens or Saw Palmetto, which is commonly used to treat BPH in men. The 14 spectra are of different retail samples, and are divided into two categories based upon the label description: adSrE, adulterated extract, and pSrE, pure extract. The adulterated samples typically have olive oil added to them, which is inactive towards BPH. There are two additional spectra included as references/outliers: evening primrose oil, labeled EPO in the data set, and olive oil, labeled OO. These latter two oils are mixtures of triglycerides for the most part, while the SrE samples are largely fatty acids. As a result, the spectra of these two groups are subtly different.
